<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://members.tripod.com/~pc93/abbskcth.htm" class="external text" title="http://members.tripod.com/~pc93/abbskcth.htm" rel="nofollow">Alvin Boyd Kuhn, Ph.D. A Biographical Sketch of his life and work</a>, by Richard Alvin Sattelberg, B.A., M.S..</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> Carter, Steven R. <i>James Jones: An American Literary Orientalist Master</i>. Urbana and Chicago: U of Illinois P, 1998, <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0252023714" class="internal">ISBN 0-252-02371-4</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Vivekananda. STRAY REMARKS ON THEOSOPHY The Complete Works of Swami Vivekananda Volume 4</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Dayananda, Humbuggery of the Theosophists. <a href="http://www.blavatskyarchives.com/dayanandahumbuggery.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.blavatskyarchives.com/dayanandahumbuggery.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.blavatskyarchives.com/dayanandahumbuggery.htm</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> See the 1987 Gill &amp; MacMillian edition of <i>Juno and the Paycock</i>,where Sean Moffatt in his notes points out O'Casey's parody of Theosophy.</li>
<li id="cite_note-15"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.tirnanoz.net" class="external text" title="http://www.tirnanoz.net" rel="nofollow">Tir Nan Oz</a></li>
</ol>
</div>
<p>T.S. Eliot references Madame Bllavatsky and theosophic doctrine in his poem, "The Cooking Egg".</p>
